        "number": 3,
        "title": "The bribed report — Jerusalem's official lie",
        "range": "28:11-15",
        "excerpt": "And when they had assembled with the elders and consulted together, they gave a large sum of money to the soldiers.",
        "body": "Matthew now does what no other evangelist does — he turns the camera on the opposition's cover-up. The juxtaposition is deliberate: *while they* (the women) *were on their way* (28:11) — that is, while the true report was running to Galilee — *some of the guard came into the city* and reported the same events to the chief priests. The chapter holds two simultaneous announcements in tension: the women's *apangello* of resurrection joy (28:8, 10) and the guards' *apangello* of resurrection terror (28:11). Same verb; same event reported; opposite responses.\n\nThe chief priests assemble with the elders — the Sanhedrin convened in emergency session — and *consulted together* (*sumboulion labontes*, 28:12). The verb appears earlier in Matthew at 12:14, 22:15, 27:1, 27:7 — every time the religious leadership conspires against Jesus. The same body that delivered Him to Pilate now meets to suppress the news of His vindication. They give *a large sum of silver* (*argurion hikana*, 28:12) to the soldiers. The word *argurion* is the same word used of Judas's thirty pieces (26:15; 27:3-9). Matthew brackets the passion with bribery: silver bought the betrayal, silver buys the cover-up. The religious establishment monetizes its opposition to Christ from beginning to end.\n\nThe fabricated story is almost comic in its self-refutation: *His disciples came by night and stole Him away while we were asleep* (28:13). Sleeping witnesses cannot testify to what happened while they slept. A Roman guard found sleeping on duty faced execution; the priests immediately reassure the soldiers that they will *win over* the governor and *keep them out of trouble* (28:14 — *amerimnos*, free from anxiety). The whole machinery of institutional power is mobilized to suppress what cannot be denied: the body is gone, and the disciples have an explanation that involves an angel of the Lord. Matthew's parenthetical note — *this story was widely spread among the Jews, and is to this day* (28:15) — indicates that the cover-up was still in circulation when Matthew wrote, decades later. Justin Martyr (*Dialogue with Trypho* 108) confirms it was still being told in the mid-second century.\n\nThe theological force of this passage is sobering: eyewitnesses to supernatural events do not automatically believe. The guards saw the earthquake (28:2), the angel (28:3-4), and presumably the empty tomb. They reported it truthfully (28:11). And then they accepted silver to lie. The resurrection is not a matter of available evidence alone; it is a matter of the heart's allegiance. Faith is moral as well as cognitive.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Argyria hikana* (28:12) — *a sufficient (large) sum of silver*. *Hikanos* means *enough*, *adequate*; here used ironically — *enough silver* to buy a lie. The same coinage used for Judas. *Diaphēmizō* (28:15) — to spread abroad, to publish widely; the verb implies official, institutional circulation, not mere rumor. The lie was sponsored, not spontaneous."
